WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:03.520
Good afternoon, everyone. We're going to start our

2
00:00:03.580 --> 00:00:07.220
session, Immune and Stromal Reprogramming Across the

3
00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:09.900
Tumor Micro and Macro Environment.

4
00:00:10.660 --> 00:00:14.420
So the field of the microenvironment, and I see many of the

5
00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:18.420
people involved in this research, which is the closest to my heart and

6
00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:19.940
my main topic,

7
00:00:21.020 --> 00:00:24.940
has been around for several decades, and I think for now, we don't need

8
00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:28.840
to convince anyone that the microenvironment is important

9
00:00:28.900 --> 00:00:32.820
after decades of research. But it also has become

10
00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:35.520
very clear that there's more to it.

11
00:00:35.780 --> 00:00:39.180
Tumors are ecosystems, and they're part of an entire

12
00:00:39.260 --> 00:00:43.100
organism, and there's also a lot of what we call now macro

13
00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:47.100
environment factors that affect tumor growth, metastasis,

14
00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:50.300
and very important, response to therapy.

15
00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:53.440
And this is what we're going to try to integrate.

16
00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:57.140
It's a huge amount of topics, but we're going to try and

17
00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:00.360
taste and integrate this in this session.

18
00:01:01.790 --> 00:01:05.660
And we have two speakers. Yuval Shaked will tell us

19
00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:09.640
about the host response to immunotherapy and how it changes the

20
00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:11.680
microenvironment, specifically ECM.

21
00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:16.440
Mitchell Fain from Fox Chase will tell us about a

22
00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:20.060
very important systemic factor at the level of the

23
00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:23.680
organism, which is aging, that affects tumor

24
00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:27.480
growth, and mostly it affects metastasis, as

25
00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:30.870
Mitchell will tell us. And then we'll finish with my

26
00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:34.760
presentation talking about stromal and immune interaction

27
00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:38.860
in organ-specific metastasis, and again, I

28
00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:42.540
hope you all enjoy it. What I didn't say is that

29
00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:43.370
at the end of

30
00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:49.140
each talk, you can ask questions, but you can also...

31
00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:53.020
There it is, the barcode. If you're too

32
00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:56.700
shy or if you're online,

33
00:01:57.780 --> 00:02:01.240
scan the barcode, and then text the questions.

34
00:02:02.340 --> 00:02:05.880
Okay. Let's start our session with our first

35
00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:07.300
speaker, Yuval Shaked.

36
00:02:17.120 --> 00:02:20.620
Thank you very much, Netta. I'd like to thank the organizers and the

37
00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:24.260
chair of this session for inviting me to this meeting.

38
00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:27.840
Today, I'm going to talk about immune checkpoint inhibitors and their association

39
00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:29.360
with the extracellular matrix,

40
00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:33.960
and all with respect to host

41
00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:35.040
response to treatment.

42
00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:36.060
So

43
00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:40.600
my lab in the last, I would say, two decades, is interested in

44
00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:44.200
resistant to treatment. And while the majority of

45
00:02:44.300 --> 00:02:48.040
studies focusing on how tumor cells are being affected by the

46
00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:51.740
treatment, we were more interested to see how the

47
00:02:51.780 --> 00:02:54.440
therapy affects many different host cells.

48
00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:58.900
They can be at the bone marrow or other organs, and they can be

49
00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:00.609
even at the tumor microenvironment.

50
00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:03.920
These are not side effects that we are talking about.

51
00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:08.040
I call it silent side effects. They are changing the tumor microenvironment,

52
00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:11.360
sometimes, as I will show you, to the tumor advantage.

53
00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:15.460
I call it the host response to anticancer treatment.

54
00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:20.660
By way of example, if you take non-tumor-bearing mice

55
00:03:21.180 --> 00:03:24.720
and you treat them with chemotherapy, and then you extract the plasma from these

56
00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:28.460
mice, and after that, you look into a different

57
00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:32.350
variety of assays that looking at the characteristics of

58
00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:36.160
cancer cells, what you can find is sometimes that the tumor cells

59
00:03:36.180 --> 00:03:39.960
become more aggressive when they are cultured with plasma

60
00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:43.140
from treated mice compared to plasma from control.

61
00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:47.560
So something in the plasma, in response to the treatment, promoted the

62
00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:50.840
activation of cancer cells. They are becoming excited.

63
00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:54.100
They are becoming proliferative and invasive.

64
00:03:54.890 --> 00:03:58.400
Another way to show it is that if you prime non-tumor-bearing mice with

65
00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:02.380
chemotherapy and then inject tumor cells to the mice, the mice

66
00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:06.160
that will show higher mortality rate are those that were

67
00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:07.580
first treated with chemotherapy.

68
00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:11.640
Again, there is something in the host in

69
00:04:11.660 --> 00:04:15.220
response to the treatment that promotes the aggressiveness

70
00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:16.579
of tumor cells.

71
00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:20.459
And these effects is not only in preclinical models.

72
00:04:20.899 --> 00:04:24.640
We can actually find them in the clinic, in samples from patients.

73
00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:28.730
Indeed, what we've done is we took plasma samples from

74
00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:32.480
colorectal cancer patients before and after treatment with FOLFOX

75
00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:36.500
chemotherapy. Before baseline and after treatment, it's

76
00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:41.000
24 hours after the first treatment, and we did the same assay that I just showed in

77
00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:44.780
mice. 70% of the patient will show increase in

78
00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:48.520
metastatic properties of the tumor cells by means

79
00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:52.440
of invasion and filtration throughout the Boyden chamber, as you can see

80
00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:52.760
here.

81
00:04:54.280 --> 00:04:58.100
So this means that the host, in response to the

82
00:04:58.180 --> 00:05:01.980
treatment, promotes a lot of regenerative factors and

83
00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:05.120
proliferative factors that support the growth of the tumor.

84
00:05:05.160 --> 00:05:08.320
It can explain tumor relapse and metastasis.

85
00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:12.220
And throughout the years, we have done work not only with

86
00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.880
chemotherapy but also with radiation and targeted

87
00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:19.640
drugs such as bortezomib, anti-angiogenic drugs, surgery,

88
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.200
and more recently, with immune checkpoint blockade.

89
00:05:23.580 --> 00:05:27.420
In each and one of these treatment modalities, we do see these

90
00:05:27.460 --> 00:05:31.290
effects. There is infiltration of a lot of immune cells into the tumor, and

91
00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:34.460
not only immune cells, but here we show only the immune cells.

92
00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:37.960
They secrete a lot of different factors that makes the tumors more

93
00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:39.000
immunosuppressive,

94
00:05:39.820 --> 00:05:42.220
and that could actually help tumors

95
00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:46.720
proliferate and metastasize.

96
00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:52.560
But one component that we neglected so far was the extracellular

97
00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:55.740
matrix. And we ask, what happened to the extracellular matrix?

98
00:05:55.790 --> 00:05:59.280
And the reason why it's important, because there is a huge

99
00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:00.000
interplay

100
00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:03.770
between different cell types and the extracellular

101
00:06:03.840 --> 00:06:07.772
matrix.Cancer-associated fibroblasts that support ECM

102
00:06:07.792 --> 00:06:10.032
remodeling. The cancer cells themselves.

103
00:06:10.432 --> 00:06:13.792
Immune cells, mostly myeloid cells that also support.

104
00:06:13.812 --> 00:06:17.402
And the interconnection between all these cells can

105
00:06:17.432 --> 00:06:21.342
promote ECM remodeling. And why ECM remodeling is

106
00:06:21.351 --> 00:06:23.852
important, because we know that it's pro-tumorigenic.

107
00:06:24.512 --> 00:06:25.892
It promotes

108
00:06:27.192 --> 00:06:29.072
resistant cell death. It

109
00:06:30.412 --> 00:06:34.292
escape the immune system. It is being used as

110
00:06:34.372 --> 00:06:38.332
a barrier, as a physical barrier, not allowing T-cells

111
00:06:38.992 --> 00:06:42.782
getting into the tumor, promote invasion and metastasis, and

112
00:06:42.892 --> 00:06:45.892
induce angiogenesis. So really, we're interested

113
00:06:46.432 --> 00:06:50.352
in the ECM. And when we say ECM remodeling, is not

114
00:06:50.452 --> 00:06:54.112
only the expression, the novosynthesis of different

115
00:06:54.312 --> 00:06:55.232
micromolecules

116
00:06:56.352 --> 00:06:56.552
that

117
00:06:57.532 --> 00:07:01.112
support the ECM, that make the ECM, but also

118
00:07:01.412 --> 00:07:03.792
post-translational modification of enzymes.

119
00:07:04.312 --> 00:07:07.352
And many of these enzymes are known to degrade the matrix.

120
00:07:07.752 --> 00:07:11.722
These are the MMPs, cathepsin, ADAMs, heparans, and

121
00:07:11.872 --> 00:07:13.532
others. They will degrade the

122
00:07:14.732 --> 00:07:18.632
ECM, the macromolecules. But in addition to them, so

123
00:07:18.672 --> 00:07:20.792
far in the world literature, we know about two

124
00:07:21.772 --> 00:07:25.712
enzymes that assemble the ECM. This is

125
00:07:25.752 --> 00:07:27.332
the lysyl oxidase, which is

126
00:07:28.572 --> 00:07:32.512
five members of one family, and the BMP1, which is upstream

127
00:07:32.852 --> 00:07:36.192
to LOX. They are known to assemble the ECM to cross-link

128
00:07:36.632 --> 00:07:38.392
collagen and elastin.

129
00:07:39.712 --> 00:07:43.232
And indeed, we found that there is increase in LOX

130
00:07:43.392 --> 00:07:47.112
expression in the lungs of mice that underwent chemotherapy.

131
00:07:47.682 --> 00:07:51.272
And this could explain why after chemotherapy, we do see

132
00:07:51.372 --> 00:07:54.772
sometimes more metastasis in mice

133
00:07:55.172 --> 00:07:56.852
that have been first treated.

134
00:07:57.672 --> 00:08:01.392
Long story short, what we showed in a previous study is that chemotherapy

135
00:08:01.772 --> 00:08:04.332
can induce ECM remodeling, and this

136
00:08:05.492 --> 00:08:09.332
support the seeding of cancer cells in the lungs

137
00:08:09.372 --> 00:08:12.652
due to the stiff tissue in the

138
00:08:12.692 --> 00:08:16.652
lungs. What we found is that CD8 T-cells

139
00:08:16.692 --> 00:08:19.712
expressing lysyl oxidase are the one that support

140
00:08:19.722 --> 00:08:22.252
chemotherapy-induced ECM remodeling.

141
00:08:23.312 --> 00:08:27.182
And when we talk about CD8 T-cells, what questions that we really were

142
00:08:27.232 --> 00:08:30.812
interested then was what happened when you give immunotherapy.

143
00:08:31.352 --> 00:08:35.033
Would you get a similar effect or changes in the ECM?

144
00:08:35.212 --> 00:08:38.052
And the story that I'm going to tell you is about the

145
00:08:38.112 --> 00:08:40.172
immunotherapy-induced ECM remodeling.

146
00:08:41.192 --> 00:08:44.961
And why it's important? It's important because we know that only 30 or

147
00:08:45.052 --> 00:08:48.932
40% of patients will benefit from immunotherapy, and the

148
00:08:49.092 --> 00:08:52.831
other patients will not. And there are many different reasons for

149
00:08:52.872 --> 00:08:55.412
resistant mechanisms for immunotherapy.

150
00:08:55.492 --> 00:08:59.342
Among them are those that are associated with immunosuppression

151
00:08:59.392 --> 00:09:02.092
activity. The ECM is immunosuppressive.

152
00:09:02.132 --> 00:09:04.672
It stores a lot of factors that are immunosuppressive.

153
00:09:05.272 --> 00:09:08.512
And also, as I mentioned, it serves as a physical barrier

154
00:09:09.272 --> 00:09:11.572
at not letting T-cells infiltrating the tumor.

155
00:09:11.632 --> 00:09:15.092
So we really were interested to study whether

156
00:09:15.472 --> 00:09:17.362
immunotherapy induced ECM remodeling.

157
00:09:18.072 --> 00:09:21.962
So in order to do it in an unbiased manner, we were looking

158
00:09:22.012 --> 00:09:25.732
for a homogeneous population of patients,

159
00:09:25.832 --> 00:09:27.352
cancer patients, that we

160
00:09:28.452 --> 00:09:28.732
have

161
00:09:29.832 --> 00:09:33.552
paired samples before treatment, usually at biopsy, and

162
00:09:33.612 --> 00:09:35.032
after immunotherapy,

163
00:09:37.992 --> 00:09:39.992
usually when you have tumor debulking.

164
00:09:40.612 --> 00:09:44.472
And we found in triple-negative breast cancer, a study that was published in

165
00:09:44.482 --> 00:09:46.892
"Nature Medicine" a few years ago.

166
00:09:47.982 --> 00:09:51.652
And we found 12 paired samples that we have the same

167
00:09:51.732 --> 00:09:55.672
patients. So we looked at the immune cells within

168
00:09:55.712 --> 00:09:59.572
these tumors and the expression, the differentially expressed genes

169
00:09:59.972 --> 00:10:01.932
between before and after treatment.

170
00:10:02.442 --> 00:10:06.092
And what we found that there are about 3,000 genes that are differentially

171
00:10:06.112 --> 00:10:09.292
expressed when you look at the whole immune system.

172
00:10:10.952 --> 00:10:14.912
And among these biological pathways that are enriched in

173
00:10:14.952 --> 00:10:17.292
these cells are usually cell matrix adhesion,

174
00:10:19.292 --> 00:10:22.931
of course, immune modulation, ECM remodeling, and

175
00:10:22.991 --> 00:10:26.972
epithelium development. And what really struck us was the fact that

176
00:10:27.292 --> 00:10:31.172
we found that the majority of the ECM remodeling and cell matrix adhesion

177
00:10:31.592 --> 00:10:35.572
were found in the T-cells. So we really were interested

178
00:10:35.692 --> 00:10:38.932
to see whether ECM remodeling can be

179
00:10:39.172 --> 00:10:42.412
recapitulated in animal models. So we used the

180
00:10:42.572 --> 00:10:44.912
4T1, the triple-negative breast cancer

181
00:10:46.032 --> 00:10:49.732
syngeneic tumors, and we asked what happened when you give anti-PD-1.

182
00:10:49.772 --> 00:10:51.812
What happened to the ECM in the tumor?

183
00:10:52.192 --> 00:10:55.992
As you can see here with Sirius Red staining, there is dense

184
00:10:56.312 --> 00:11:00.192
ECM collagen I and III staining after

185
00:11:00.292 --> 00:11:03.392
anti-PD-1 compared to the IgG control.

186
00:11:03.832 --> 00:11:07.432
Here is another tumor model, such as Lewis lung carcinoma.

187
00:11:07.832 --> 00:11:11.232
You can see again these fibers, massive

188
00:11:11.892 --> 00:11:15.772
dense fibers following anti-PD-1 compared to control.

189
00:11:17.692 --> 00:11:20.592
Since our suspect are the T-cells based on the

190
00:11:22.032 --> 00:11:25.952
single-cell RNA sequencing, as well as based on the previous studies we

191
00:11:25.972 --> 00:11:29.792
have done, and the fact that it's anti-PD-1 treatment, we

192
00:11:29.872 --> 00:11:32.972
ask what happens when you don't have T-cells.

193
00:11:33.012 --> 00:11:36.932
We use SCID mice that are lacking B and T-cells, and we did the

194
00:11:36.952 --> 00:11:40.912
same experiment. As you can see here, after anti-PD-1, there is no changes in

195
00:11:40.952 --> 00:11:44.332
ECM in the tumors. And in fact, when we

196
00:11:44.372 --> 00:11:45.012
now

197
00:11:46.272 --> 00:11:50.172
adaptively transfer T-cells from normal mice into these

198
00:11:50.572 --> 00:11:54.232
SCID mice, you can restore the ECM remodeling

199
00:11:54.332 --> 00:11:58.272
after anti-PD-1 therapy, suggesting that T-cells indeed

200
00:11:58.312 --> 00:12:01.932
responsible, either directly or indirectly, to the

201
00:12:01.972 --> 00:12:05.642
ECM remodeling. So we wanted to study what could be the

202
00:12:05.692 --> 00:12:07.692
reason, and we looked at the

203
00:12:08.612 --> 00:12:12.032
different enzymes, post-translational modification of the ECM,

204
00:12:12.492 --> 00:12:15.792
and we found that BMP1 and LOX are

205
00:12:15.852 --> 00:12:19.656
upregulated in the T-cells.We validated

206
00:12:19.716 --> 00:12:23.656
it by looking into conditioned medium of CD8

207
00:12:23.696 --> 00:12:26.216
T cells, but we also find it systemically.

208
00:12:26.276 --> 00:12:28.756
We found that also in the plasma of

209
00:12:28.776 --> 00:12:32.576
anti-PD-1-treated mice, we have higher levels

210
00:12:32.876 --> 00:12:34.316
of BMP1.

211
00:12:36.356 --> 00:12:39.176
What is BMP1? It's a bone morphogenic protein 1.

212
00:12:39.436 --> 00:12:43.176
It plays a role in the formation and development of the extracellular matrix.

213
00:12:43.676 --> 00:12:45.896
How it does that? It does it in a variety of ways.

214
00:12:46.336 --> 00:12:49.896
It cleaves procollagen, usually I, II, and III, into

215
00:12:50.156 --> 00:12:52.176
active collagen, fibrillar collagen.

216
00:12:52.636 --> 00:12:56.536
It also cleaves pro-LOX, make it active LOX,

217
00:12:56.696 --> 00:13:00.376
then it can cross-link collagen and elastin, and it also

218
00:13:00.396 --> 00:13:03.696
release TGF-beta from the ECM.

219
00:13:04.356 --> 00:13:07.716
BMP1 in tumors, overexpression is known to be

220
00:13:07.796 --> 00:13:10.196
pro-tumorigenic and support metastasis.

221
00:13:10.656 --> 00:13:11.076
And there is

222
00:13:12.596 --> 00:13:16.436
an inhibitor for BMP1, a small molecule that developed by

223
00:13:16.476 --> 00:13:16.876
Pfizer,

224
00:13:17.676 --> 00:13:20.606
for fibrosis, not for cancer, and

225
00:13:21.156 --> 00:13:25.066
it's called UK-383367. I will

226
00:13:25.076 --> 00:13:28.996
call it from now on UK. So the obvious experience that one would like to

227
00:13:29.036 --> 00:13:32.956
try is to see what happens when you combine anti-PD-1 with

228
00:13:33.016 --> 00:13:36.896
the BMP1 inhibitor. So the BMP1 inhibitor as

229
00:13:37.076 --> 00:13:40.976
a small molecule and short half-life, you need to give on a daily basis,

230
00:13:41.396 --> 00:13:44.076
whereas the PD-1, you give twice a week.

231
00:13:44.116 --> 00:13:47.296
And again, you use the 4T1 breast cancer model that is

232
00:13:47.336 --> 00:13:50.916
resistant to anti-PD-1. But once you use this combination,

233
00:13:51.336 --> 00:13:55.076
now you can see the tumors become sensitive to anti-PD-1

234
00:13:55.116 --> 00:13:57.236
therapy. And why they are sensitive?

235
00:13:57.636 --> 00:14:01.176
They are sensitive because if you look at the ECM, there is reduced

236
00:14:01.236 --> 00:14:04.156
ECM in the combination treatment compared to the

237
00:14:04.236 --> 00:14:07.406
anti-PD-1. And what else you can see, that there is more

238
00:14:07.456 --> 00:14:10.956
infiltration of activated T cells

239
00:14:11.036 --> 00:14:14.936
into this tumor, suggesting that blocking BMP1

240
00:14:14.996 --> 00:14:18.796
in combination with anti-PD-1 can actually make resistant

241
00:14:18.816 --> 00:14:21.176
tumors sensitive tumors to therapy.

242
00:14:21.876 --> 00:14:25.776
But we wanted to really, because we saw that in the plasma there

243
00:14:25.816 --> 00:14:29.376
is increase in BMP1, so there is systemic increase in

244
00:14:29.416 --> 00:14:33.296
BMP1, but not only in T cell. We really wanted to figure out

245
00:14:33.516 --> 00:14:36.376
whether the BMP1 in T cell is as responsible.

246
00:14:37.576 --> 00:14:40.956
So what we did next was we did an experiment where we

247
00:14:41.056 --> 00:14:44.076
basically took the SCID mice, and we adaptively

248
00:14:44.116 --> 00:14:47.656
transferred T cells either expressing or not expressing

249
00:14:47.676 --> 00:14:51.036
BMP1 using CRISPR-Cas9, and so you can see that there is

250
00:14:51.476 --> 00:14:54.296
knockdown of BMP1, and then we gave anti-PD-1 treatment.

251
00:14:54.696 --> 00:14:58.416
And you can see that when you don't have BMP1, there is no ECM

252
00:14:58.496 --> 00:15:02.256
remodeling in these tumors. Suggesting that it's sufficient to

253
00:15:02.296 --> 00:15:06.176
block BMP1 just in T cells in order to get

254
00:15:06.236 --> 00:15:09.276
the effect on the ECM. So it doesn't

255
00:15:10.056 --> 00:15:12.376
necessarily have to be a systemic effect.

256
00:15:12.436 --> 00:15:16.176
It could be really local effect with the BMP1 in the T cells.

257
00:15:17.616 --> 00:15:21.276
And we figured out the mechanism, how

258
00:15:21.356 --> 00:15:24.936
actually it works. So if you have anti-PD-1, it

259
00:15:25.016 --> 00:15:28.845
actually activate the T cells. In the granules, you have

260
00:15:28.936 --> 00:15:32.596
stored BMP1 that is secreted after activation.

261
00:15:32.636 --> 00:15:36.536
The BMP1, as we said, act on the ECM and

262
00:15:37.616 --> 00:15:39.976
makes collagen,

263
00:15:41.096 --> 00:15:45.016
activate LOX, and therefore, make

264
00:15:45.076 --> 00:15:48.976
more ECM or ECM remodeling. But it also,

265
00:15:49.056 --> 00:15:51.776
as I mentioned, release the TGF-beta from the ECM.

266
00:15:51.836 --> 00:15:53.176
And once it release it from the

267
00:15:54.916 --> 00:15:57.576
ECM, it can bind back to the receptor, the

268
00:15:57.636 --> 00:16:01.236
TGF-beta receptor, that now will

269
00:16:01.296 --> 00:16:05.016
exhaust the T cells. So when we have kind of a positive

270
00:16:05.076 --> 00:16:08.656
loop that will inhibit the activity of T cells

271
00:16:08.716 --> 00:16:12.676
once you give anti-PD-1. And to prove that, here I'll show

272
00:16:12.716 --> 00:16:16.236
you that when you take T cells, dump them cells in vitro, and you add

273
00:16:16.316 --> 00:16:19.376
anti-PD-1, you get activation of the T cells.

274
00:16:19.836 --> 00:16:23.796
But if you do it on the experiment when you have ECM in

275
00:16:23.816 --> 00:16:27.576
the culture, then you see that after anti-PD-1 treatment, there is no

276
00:16:27.616 --> 00:16:31.226
activation of CD8 T cells. But you can restore the activation

277
00:16:31.776 --> 00:16:35.216
if you block either the TGF-beta receptor or

278
00:16:35.276 --> 00:16:38.956
you block BMP1 activity by the enzyme, as I

279
00:16:38.996 --> 00:16:42.936
mentioned. So what you have here is not only inhibition

280
00:16:42.996 --> 00:16:45.996
of the physical barrier, but you also have

281
00:16:46.356 --> 00:16:49.876
ignition of the T cell, making sure that they not undergo

282
00:16:50.176 --> 00:16:53.216
exhaustion and actually work better in this case.

283
00:16:54.476 --> 00:16:58.076
So due to these studies, we decided to develop an

284
00:16:58.136 --> 00:17:01.726
antibody-drug conjugate. I call it the first-in-class antibody drug conjugate

285
00:17:02.156 --> 00:17:05.336
because usually the antibody drug conjugate, what do they do?

286
00:17:05.376 --> 00:17:07.816
We have three components that are very important.

287
00:17:07.836 --> 00:17:11.816
The first one is the specificity, which is based on the antibody that

288
00:17:11.876 --> 00:17:15.696
you use. You have a linker that is very important to know how many

289
00:17:15.757 --> 00:17:19.036
payloads you put on each antibody and if there is

290
00:17:19.517 --> 00:17:20.116
a

291
00:17:21.576 --> 00:17:23.977
steric interference with the antibody.

292
00:17:24.017 --> 00:17:27.997
And you have the payload that, in our case, is a BMP1 inhibitor

293
00:17:28.036 --> 00:17:31.756
rather than a cytotoxic drug. Currently, most of the

294
00:17:31.796 --> 00:17:33.496
ADCs that are

295
00:17:34.316 --> 00:17:34.896
in the clinic

296
00:17:35.716 --> 00:17:39.396
are based on payloads of tubulin inhibitors

297
00:17:39.856 --> 00:17:42.896
and DNA-modifying agents, which are cytotoxic agent.

298
00:17:43.316 --> 00:17:46.876
So what we decided to do is to use an enzyme inhibitor as a

299
00:17:46.916 --> 00:17:50.606
payload, and that we will know that we'll harness the immune system

300
00:17:50.896 --> 00:17:53.736
and will reduce the frequency of drug administration.

301
00:17:53.776 --> 00:17:56.015
We don't need to give the UK on a daily basis.

302
00:17:56.096 --> 00:17:58.786
It's on the antibody, so it may

303
00:17:59.836 --> 00:18:03.236
stay for a longer time. So then we tried the same

304
00:18:03.516 --> 00:18:05.896
treatment, but this time using the ADC.

305
00:18:06.276 --> 00:18:10.216
And you can see that just by adding the ADC, you get, again, tumor growth

306
00:18:10.296 --> 00:18:10.956
retardation

307
00:18:11.996 --> 00:18:15.676
in this 4T1 tumor model. We've tried additional models such as

308
00:18:15.756 --> 00:18:17.656
melanoma and Lewis lung carcinoma.

309
00:18:18.706 --> 00:18:22.656
And why it happens? It happens because it reuses the

310
00:18:22.676 --> 00:18:26.636
ECM content or the remodeling in the tumors with

311
00:18:26.656 --> 00:18:30.348
the ADC, and you get ignition of-Or a

312
00:18:30.828 --> 00:18:34.608
full activation of the T cells that infiltrate into these tumors.

313
00:18:34.928 --> 00:18:38.428
So you don't have the physical barrier, and you have more

314
00:18:38.448 --> 00:18:41.668
activation of the T cells due to this ADC.

315
00:18:43.548 --> 00:18:47.108
Last but not least, what we were also interested in is to see,

316
00:18:47.388 --> 00:18:50.858
like this is all preclinical models, what happened in clinical

317
00:18:50.888 --> 00:18:53.148
situation. So we were

318
00:18:54.628 --> 00:18:58.268
collaborating with Roche on a clinical study that was done in

319
00:18:58.328 --> 00:18:58.748
Essen,

320
00:19:00.148 --> 00:19:00.488
by

321
00:19:01.388 --> 00:19:04.488
Sven Brandau, and we actually looked at

322
00:19:05.248 --> 00:19:08.268
small number of patients where we, again, have a

323
00:19:08.368 --> 00:19:12.108
biopsy and after treatment with immunotherapy of

324
00:19:12.328 --> 00:19:14.408
head and neck squamous cell carcinoma.

325
00:19:14.748 --> 00:19:18.288
And you can see that almost all patients show higher

326
00:19:18.908 --> 00:19:22.748
levels of ECM remodeling after treatment with immunotherapy.

327
00:19:23.388 --> 00:19:26.948
And if you look on the immune cells, you can see that CD8 T cells

328
00:19:27.268 --> 00:19:30.968
express higher levels of BMP1 after treatment, suggesting

329
00:19:31.328 --> 00:19:34.288
that what we have seen in preclinical model

330
00:19:34.527 --> 00:19:38.448
might be relevant to the clinic. And

331
00:19:38.508 --> 00:19:42.228
this is, I would like to conclude that ECM

332
00:19:42.268 --> 00:19:46.088
remodeling after immunotherapy is associated with ECM remodeling.

333
00:19:47.008 --> 00:19:49.148
This is done due to de novo synthesis.

334
00:19:49.248 --> 00:19:53.168
I didn't show you, but we have done also work on showing that there is more

335
00:19:53.228 --> 00:19:57.098
fibrillar collagens that is highly expressed and activation

336
00:19:57.128 --> 00:19:59.828
of post-translational modification by enzymes.

337
00:20:00.688 --> 00:20:04.528
In addition to cancer-associated fibroblasts, myeloid cells are also

338
00:20:04.548 --> 00:20:08.528
